                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding xml:id="binding" contemporary="true Ethiopian">
                              <p>
                                The manuscript was repaired several times, as testify the various threads visible on the spine and holes drilled through the boards.
                                However, the materials and the techniques used are compatible with those of the Ethiopian binding tradition.
                                The boards and the cover are possibly contemporary with the main texts.</p>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="bindingMaterial">
                                The book is bound in <material key="wood">wooden</material> boards covered with dark brown blind-tooled <material
                                key="leather">leather</material>. The inner sides of both boards are decorated with <material key="textile">textile</material> <term key="textileInlay">inlays</term>
                                featuring vertical yellow and light blue vertical stripes on a red background.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="Boards">
                                The boards are cut to the same size as the bookblock and present external shallow bevels.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Cover" color="dark brown">
                                Full dark-brown leather cover.
                                The turn-ins have been trimmed out and at the corners they form butt mitres.
                                <term key="additionalLeatherPatch">Additional leather patches</term> used to fill the gap between the turn-ins
                                but they have been removed, presumably to resew the bookblock.
                                The cover shows a blind-tooled decoration, identical on both sides of the cover. The turn-ins and the edges are decorated as well.
                                The decoration consists of three concentric frames surrounding a central rectangular panel featuring a Latin cross.
                                Frames composed by the repetition of single tools, enclosed between <term key="tripleStraightLine">triple straight lines</term>,
                                alternate with empty ones.
                                Proceeding from the outer to the inner frame, the repeating decoration motifs are <term key="crissCross">criss-crosses</term>,
                                and <term key="wavyLine">wavy lines</term> with <term key="doubleCircle">double circles</term> between them.
                                The cross is formed by <term key="XForm">X-form</term> motifs between <term key="singleStraightLine">single straight lines</term>.
                                At the ends of the arms of the cross there are <term key="corniForm">corniform</term> motifs and three <term key="doubleCircle">double circles</term>.
                                Double straight lines outline the shape of the cross, dividing the area around it in four panels.
                                In the panels at the foot of the cross, the triple straight lines form two triangles, each surmounted by a <term key="doubleCircle">double circle</term>.
                                In the panels above, they intersect forming a <foreign xml:lang="la">crux decussata</foreign>. <term key="doubleCircle">Double circles</term> are stamped
                                at the intersections of the straight lines and at the corners of the empty frames.
                                A <term key="tripleStraightLine">triple straight line</term> runs along the edges of the boards with <term key="doubleCircle">double circles</term> stamped
                                at intervals.
                                Turn-ins are decorated with the <foreign xml:lang="la">crux decussata</foreign> and <term key="doubleCircle">double circle</term> motifs.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b4" type="SewingStations">4</decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b5">
                                Chainstitch sewing on four sewing stations (two pairs); periodic fold pattern; Z-plied threads.
                                Between each pair of sewing stations there are two lengths of thread.
                                The sewing has been repaired several times with different threads. Groups of leaves are stitched together
                                through the inner margin.
                              </decoNote>
                              <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="Spine">
                                The back of the leather cover, together with the endbands, has been removed to resew the manuscript.
                                A small fragment of the leather spine is still attached at the head.
                                The small holes close to the head and tail of the quires testify to the former presence of endbands.
                              </decoNote>
                            </binding>
